4. In the field of information exchange they have:


(i) said that they will allow into the USSR in 1976 a further 18 non-communist Western newspapers, including a small number of copies of the Financial Times;

(ii) concluded arrangements with a number of Western countries (including the United Kingdom) for the reciprocal grant of multiple entry-exit visas for permanently accredited journalists;

(iii) abolished the requirements for prior authority before journalists can send tapes and undeveloped film out of the USSR;

(iv) anounced their intention of making, as from 1st March, a small improvement in the conditions of travel for foreign journalists based in Moscow. (Her Majesty's Government have responded by pledging an equivalent improvement for Soviet journalists resident in Britain.)
